    {
      "id": "9f79c5770ab05ed4d7090eebe78cb189c47f062e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 12,
        "name": "wangdi",
        "email": "di.wang@intel.com",
        "username": "wangdi",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-03-14 23:04:04.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI am a little confused here. For \"passing\" you mean the test should literally pass, i.e. skip, or actually run the test and pass?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "a86715232920cc8c65bc62420ca4319c10ef2492",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2012-03-15 07:20:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.2/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/32a241fe-6e6c-11e1-b737-5254004bbbd3).  Ran 13 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "88cf8f416225d8c2a6ff1fa3de36d2e9f6a75a3b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-03-15 07:36:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nWhat I mean is that in the normal test case, the \"skip_env\" will not be hit, the test will PASS, and it may appear that this patch is OK.\n\nIf the \"skip_env\" check is hit in developer manual interop testing, it will report SKIP and not cause a test failure, but if there is official release interop testing done then \"skip_env\" will cause the test (and hence the whole build) to FAIL instead of SKIP.  Looking at the code:\n\n skip_env () {\n     $FAIL_ON_SKIP_ENV && error false $@ || skip $@\n }\n\nMy understanding is that FAIL_ON_SKIP_ENV=true for release builds, or at least that was the case at CFS/Sun/Oracle.  The intent is that \"skip_env\" is to ensure tests which might legitimately be difficult for developers to run (e.g. MPI tests), but should not be skipped during automated testing or there will be a hole in our test coverage.\n\nSo, because this test cannot possibly pass if it is run against a server that does not have support for these stats, the test should just use the normal \"skip\" instead of \"skip_env\", as I had originally suggested in my comment.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "2851ad16cfd1da4b42ab9d51c3f08e35bd6e7c5e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-03-15 12:11:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nBuild Started http://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/5286/ ",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "df41764dcab7f6eb747f14cc21e86eb8e8090cf3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-03-15 12:34:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Verified\n\nBuild Successful \n \nhttp://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/5286/ : SUCCESS",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "5d7174bcb7d71e2ad38fa1cfa4c2a69aefc5154a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 131,
        "name": "Jian Yu",
        "email": "yujian@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "yujian"
      },
      "date": "2012-03-16 10:11:31.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(4 inline comments)\n\n> My understanding is that FAIL_ON_SKIP_ENV=true for release builds, or at least that was the case at CFS/Sun/Oracle. The intent is that \"skip_env\" is to ensure tests which might legitimately be difficult for developers to run (e.g. MPI tests), but should not be skipped during automated testing or there will be a hole in our test coverage.\n\nUnfortunately, FAIL_ON_SKIP_ENV is not set to true in the current autotest config file. During the release/build testing cycles, we usually check the test outputs to see whether some tests are skipped due to the environment issues, and if there are any, we would adjust the corresponding variables to meet the requirements and re-run the tests. Usually, this is little work because we have known how to set proper values to meet the requirements of almost all of the tests.\n\n\n> So, because this test cannot possibly pass if it is run against a server that does not have support for these stats, the test should just use the normal \"skip\" instead of \"skip_env\", as I had originally suggested in my comment.\n\nYes, agreed. Please use \"skip\".",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
